&quot;;`, because you can&#39;t do `std::cin &gt;&gt; &quot;
&quot;;`. The `&quot;
&quot;` is a C-string literal, which is of a type `const char[2]`, which, in above case, decays to `const char*`. You do not have to understand what decaying is, but you have to understand that with `std::cin`, you cannot use to it modify something that&#39;s `const`.

Furthermore, the following: `std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;This is the input: 
&quot; &gt;&gt; varname &gt;&gt; &quot;
&quot;;` can&#39;t work either. If you want to send multiple elements to `std::cout`, use `&lt;&lt;` everywhere - don&#39;t mix them with `&gt;&gt;`.

To summarise:

- `std::cin &gt;&gt; varname &gt;&gt; &quot;
&quot;;` -&gt; `std::cin &gt;&gt; varname;`
- `std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;This is the input: 
